        <div class="post">
            <h2 class="title"><font color="#737373">What is ArpON?</font></h2>
            <div class="entry" align="justify">
                <p>
                <b>ArpON</b> (<b>ARP handler inspection</b>) is a Host-based solution that make the <a href="documentation.html#29">ARP standardized protocol</a> secure in order to avoid the Man In The Middle (MITM) attack through the ARP spoofing, ARP cache poisoning or ARP poison routing attack.
                <br><br>
                This is possible using three kinds of anti ARP spoofing techniques:
                <br>

                <ol>
                <li>
                <b><a href="documentation.html#14">SARPI</a></b> (<b><a href="documentation.html#14">Static ARP Inspection</a></b>) for the statically configured networks without DHCP;
                </li>

                <li>
                <b><a href="documentation.html#14">DARPI</a></b> (<b><a href="documentation.html#14">Dynamic ARP Inspection</a></b>) for the dynamically configured networks with DHCP;
                </li>

                <li>
                <b><a href="documentation.html#14">HARPI</a></b> (<b><a href="documentation.html#14">Hybrid ARP Inspection</a></b>) for the statically and dynamically configured networks with DHCP.
                </li>
                </ol>
                The <b>goal</b> of ArpON is therefore to provide a secure and efficient <a href="documentation.html#12">network daemon</a> that provides the <a href="documentation.html#14">SARPI</a>, <a href="documentation.html#14">DARPI</a> and <a href="documentation.html#14">HARPI</a> anti ARP spoofing technique, thus making the ARP standardized protocol secure from any foreign intrusion.
                </p>
            </div>
            <p class="meta"><a href="#TOP" class="permalink">Top</a></p>
